Here's a JavaScript function that uses regex to extract a three character code from a filename in the specified format:

```javascript
function extractCodeFromFilename(filename) {
  const regex = /^(\d+)-([a-zA-Z0-9]{3})\.usfm$/;
  return filename.match(regex)[2];
}
```

This function takes a filename as input and returns the three character code. The regular expression `^(\d+)-([a-zA-Z0-9]{3})\.usfm$` matches filenames that start with one or more digits, followed by a hyphen, then exactly three characters that can be upper or lower case letters or digits, and finally the ".usfm" extension.

You can use this function like this:
```javascript
const filename = "57-1Jn.usfm";
console.log(extractCodeFromFilename(filename)); // Outputs: 1Jn
```
